post_text:
‚ú®In today's Teacher Feature, we welcome Ms. Molly Kruzel.
Ms. Kruzel began her teaching career in Seoul, South Korea, where she taught kindergarten English. Since returning home to Arizona, she has been teaching Pre-K. Ms. Kruzel holds a bachelor‚Äôs degree in Education from Faith International University and a second bachelor‚Äôs degree in Biblical Studies from Calvary Chapel Bible College. Ms. Kruzel believes that the early childhood years are the most formative, tender years in a child‚Äôs life, and she is honored to be part of the Archway North Phoenix kindergarten team. She hopes to share her love of music with her young scholars and desires to inspire them to love learning and always seek the truth. In her free time, Ms. Kruzel plays guitar for her church‚Äôs worship band and is learning to play the piano. She also enjoys green tea lattes, thrifting, and watching British and Korean TV shows! * Fun fact, this picture was taken at Gyeongbokgung Palace in Seoul built in the 1300's.‚ú®
Have a great day Argonauts!
#argonautpride

post_text:
‚ú®Back to School- Teacher Feature. Argonauts please help us welcome Ms. Hay to our North Phoenix community. She is joining our wonderful ESS Team for both ANP and NPX
‚ú®Here‚Äôs a short bio! I knew in high school that I wanted to be a teacher! I graduated with my bachelor‚Äôs in elementary education from Grand Canyon University. (Way back in the dark ages.). I double minored in German and Music Education. After teaching first through third grades, I went back to school and got my master‚Äôs degree in special education, to work with deaf and hard-of-hearing children. I have been in education since 1997! In my spare time, I enjoy working in my backyard garden, cooking, playing the piano, and spending time with Watson, my almost-two year old Shih-Tzu. An interesting fact about me is that I walk with Watson on the treadmill, when it‚Äôs too hot to walk outside in the summertime. I also got stuck in an elevator (all by myself) when I was a foreign exchange student in Germany.
Welcome Ms. Hay üôÇ
#argonautpride
#gogladiators

Virtual Athenaeum: Before emails and social media became the standard, letter writing was the most common form of relaying news and sharing thoughts across the miles. Today, scholars will hear about the letters exchanged between John and Abigail Adams at the time of the American Revolution and think about who in their own lives might make a good ‚Äúpen pal‚Äù.

To make your own stationery, all you need is:
Paper
Pen or Pencil
Colored pencils, markers, paints, stamps, stickers, etc.

For more videos or to register for After-School Athenaeum for Fall 2020-21, please visit:
www.GreatHeartsAmerica.org/Athenaeum

Virtual Athenaeum: Abstract artist Paul Klee inspires today‚Äôs lesson working with shapes and bold colors to mimic this famous artist‚Äôs work. Scholars will learn a little about the artist and be led in a step by step instruction to reproduce Klee‚Äôs famous ‚ÄúCat and Bird‚Äù painting.

To create your own Paul Klee inspired masterpiece, you will need:
Paper
Pencil
Black marker
Crayons or other coloring supply

Virtual Athenaeum: Do you have a lot of small crayon pieces left over at the end of the school year? Learn how you can recycle old crayons and make them good as new again!

**Be sure to have an adult help with this project!**

All you need to make your own crayon creation is:
old, broken crayons (with the paper removed)

If using the oven:
muffin tin (or silicone baking mold)
muffin tin liners (or non-stick spray)

Bake at about 200 degrees for about 10 min

If using the microwave:
Microwave-safe bowl, dish or mold

Microwave on low heat for approximately 5-6 minutes (stop and stir every 2 minutes)

**Be careful after crayons are melted as they will be very hot. Wait until your crayons are completely cooled before taking them out of the mold and using them. Remember, be sure to have an adult help with this project!**

For more videos or to register for After-School Athenaeum 2020-21, please visit:
www.GreatHeartsAmerica.org/Athenaeum

Register before May 31st and save $75!

Last day of school posting!
Fourth grade enjoyed a fun week of Zooming with their teachers! Classes played battleship, baked cookies, played trivia games, and got to ask questions to the teachers and Mr. Fee!

The teacher recommended some books for summer reading, and we revisited the first day of school! On the first day of school, scholars wrote down things they were excited about, worried about, and curiosities. Last Day of school posting!
3rd grade had several happy celebrations for the end of the year! Ms. Marshall and Ms. Byrnes' class dressed up in goofy outfits, snacks in hand, and took turns sharing their favorite memories from 3rd grade. Ms. Diesing and Ms. Allan's class also dressed up in silly outfits and shared their highs and lows from the year with each other. water, dish soap, sugar

stick, pencil, string, pipe cleaners, hanger, wire, shoe lace, etc.
What did you use to make your bubble-wand?

post_text:
In dedication to our Graduating Class of 2020 from North Phoenix Prep, here they all are! üòÅ More fun videos and pictures to come.
Did you Know?
North Phoenix Prep has 27 seniors graduating in the class of 2020! (This is our 3rd graduating class, and our class sizes continue to grow with each year.) Thanks to #CommunityInvestment, our teachers were able to operate at full capacity despite challenges from COVID-19 to ensure our students graduate as planned this year, along with helping all of our students K-11, stay on track and ensure they are ready to move on to the next grade level.
Learn more about our #CommunityInvestment campaign and how your support helps all of our teachers and the operation of our schools @archwaynorthphoenix.org/support
You can also reach out to our Academy Giving Manager, Jackie Curtis @jcurtis@archwaynorthphoenix.org with further questions.
Thank you for supporting our Great Hearts North Phoenix Schools ‚ù§Ô∏è

Dedication to our North Phoenix Prep seniors this week!
Taking us back to when we were all on campus enjoying one of our most favorite days, Literacy Day. Literacy day was such an exciting day where our entire campus K-12 dressed up as their favorite book character, and we spent the day celebrating the love of reading. Our seniors really enjoyed spending time with and reading to all the ANP students. Today, one of our seniors would like to share one of her favorite books with you. So if you haven't selected a bedtime story yet, enjoy this story time with Alana Curtis.

post_text:
Virtual Athenaeum: In times of anxiety, we look for ways to develop peace and bring comfort into our minds and hearts. In our first Virtual Athenaeum lesson, scholars will hear the story of the Guatemalan Worry Doll and contemplate ways they can talk about and process their own concerns in challenging times.

Supplies needed for today‚Äôs activity:
Household supplies and craft remnants such as clothespins, twist ties, gum wrappers, pipe cleaners, string, and/or yarn, tape or glue, and scissors.

For more Virtual Athenaeum and to learn more about our programs, please visit us at www.GreatHeartsAmerica.org/Athenaeum/AZ
